div.p:
               The King hath a Superior, to wit, God; alſo the Law, by which he is made a King;
II. Bracton his Words touching the Supream Power.
                   likewiſe his Court, namely, the Earls and Barons; becauſe they are called Comites, as being the King's Fellows (or Companions:) And he who hath a Fellow (or Aſſociate) hath a Maſter. And therefore, if the King ſhall be without a Bridle, that is, without Law, they ought to impoſe a Bridle on him, unleſs they themſelves, with the King, ſhall be without Bridle; and then the Subject ſhall cry out, and ſay, O Lord Jeſus Chriſt, do thou bind their Jaws with Bitt and Bridle, &c.
